<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much soil do I need for a 4x8 raised bed?", answer: "A standard 4 × 8 foot raised bed that is 12 inches deep holds 32 cubic feet, which is about 1.2 cubic yards. Using a 60/30/10 Mel's Mix ratio, that is roughly 19 cubic feet of topsoil, 10 cubic feet of compost, and 3 cubic feet of aeration material like perlite or coarse bark. A bed that is 6 inches deep holds exactly half that volume, and one that is 18 inches deep holds 48 cubic feet." },
  { question: "What is Mel's Mix?", answer: "Mel's Mix is the soil recipe popularized by Square Foot Gardening author Mel Bartholomew: one-third compost, one-third peat moss or coir, and one-third coarse vermiculite, by volume. It drains well, holds moisture, and supplies nutrients without native topsoil. The original Mel's Mix avoids topsoil entirely; modern variations often replace the vermiculite with perlite because it is cheaper and more available, and some gardeners substitute a quality topsoil for the peat to save money." },
  { question: "Do I need to fill the whole raised bed with soil?", answer: "You do not have to, especially for deep beds. Beds deeper than 12 inches can be filled at the bottom with layers of logs, branches, wood chips, leaves, and straw — the hugelkultur method — which saves money on soil and releases nutrients as it breaks down. Only the top 8 to 12 inches needs to be premium soil blend because that is where most plant roots actually grow." },
  { question: "How much does it cost to fill a raised bed?", answer: "A 4 × 8 × 12 inch raised bed filled with bagged Mel's Mix costs roughly 150 to 250 dollars depending on component prices. Using bulk topsoil and compost from a landscape supplier drops the cost to 50 to 100 dollars for the same bed. The savings grow with bed count — filling four beds bulk is about 250 dollars total, versus 800 to 1,000 dollars in bags." },
  { question: "Can I reuse raised bed soil next year?", answer: "Yes — raised bed soil should last many years. Each spring, top up with 1 to 2 inches of fresh compost to replace settled volume and replenish nutrients. Every 3 to 5 years, add a fresh dose of aeration material (perlite or coarse bark) because it compacts over time. Only replace all the soil if the bed gets root knot nematodes or a soil-borne disease." }
]) %>

